d, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1241–1303":"1241–1303","1214–1303":"1214–1303","1241–Female":"1241–Deceased","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1218–1268":"1218–1268","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1214":"1214","1268":"1268","1345":"1345","1299":"1299","1241":"1241","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1218":"1218","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Oxford, , Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Clifford Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Clifford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Locke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Dutch, and German: variant of   Lock  .","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Løkke</b>: habitational name from a farm name, from Old Norse <i>lykkja</i> ‘enclosure’.","Chinese: variant of   Lok  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lock","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived near an enclosure, a place that could be locked, Middle English <i>loke</i>, Old English <i>loca</i>. Middle English <i>loke</i> also came to be used to denote a barrier, in particular a barrier on a river which could be opened and closed at will, and, by extension, a bridge. The surname may thus also have been a metonymic occupational name for a lock-keeper.","English, Dutch, and German: nickname for a person with fine hair, or curly hair, from Middle English <i>loc</i>, Middle High German <i>lock(e)</i> ‘lock (of hair), curl’. Compare   Lok  .","Americanized form of German   Loch  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":18,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":49,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Locke was born in 1241, in Clifford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Locke, was 24 and his mother, Lucy de Quincy, was 23. He married F Locke in 1259, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1303, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1241–1303":"1241–1303","1214–1303":"1214–1303","1241–Female":"1241–Surnud","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1218–1268":"1218–1268","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1214":"1214","1268":"1268","1345":"1345","1299":"1299","1241":"1241","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1218":"1218","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","London, Middlesex, E